  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is negative gearing on an investment property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Negative gearing occurs when the costs of owning an investment property — including interest, rates, insurance, land tax, property management, and maintenance — exceed the rental income it generates. The resulting net loss can be offset against other income, reducing the owner's taxable income. The strategy assumes that capital growth over time will outweigh the annual losses."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "When does negative gearing stop making sense for Brisbane investors?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Negative gearing stops making financial sense when the annual losses are no longer justified by the expected future capital gain. This assessment changes over time as interest rates, land tax, and other holding costs increase, as rental yields compress relative to costs, or as the investor's income or personal tax position changes. A financial adviser and accountant should model this with your specific numbers."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do I pay capital gains tax when I sell a negatively geared property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. When you sell an investment property in Australia, capital gains tax applies to the difference between your sale price and your cost base (adjusted purchase price plus eligible costs). If you have owned the property for more than 12 months, you are eligible for the 50% CGT discount. Your accountant will calculate the net CGT liability based on your specific situation."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I sell my negatively geared property before or after 30 June?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The timing of settlement relative to 30 June affects which financial year the capital gain falls into. If you have a large capital gain, settling after 30 June defers the tax by a year. This is a common planning consideration, but whether it is the right approach depends on your income in each year and your accountant's advice."
      }
    }
  ]
}
